  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Provision of Critical Humanitarian Assistance Including Coordination and Access to Ensure the Provision of Emergency Shelter/NFI/CCCM and Protection Activities to People Affected by Earthquake</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The 14 August earthquake in southwestern Haiti destroyed buildings and homes, damaged critical infrastructure and roads. The Sud, Grand&apos;Anse and Nippes departments were the hardest hit. As of 18 August, 136,000 families have been affected (more than 650,000 people). Many of these people have fled their homes, fearful that they will collapse, seeking refuge in evacuation shelters and host families. In addition, protection issues, such as trafficking and access to emergency services are an increasing concern for humanitarian partners on the ground, notably for the most vulnerable populations (women, girls, people with disabilities, and the elderly). The proposed intervention aims at providing critical humanitarian assistance to 45,000 vulnerable people affected by the August 2021 earthquake. This includes strengthening access activities to ensure the provision of emergency shelter, non-food items, camp coordination and camp management and protection activities.</narrative>
  </description>
